event_investment_decisions.event_description:
In the upcoming MLB game, scheduled for September 17 at 7:40PM ET:
If the Los Angeles Angels win, the market will resolve to “Angels”.
If the Milwaukee Brewers win, the market will resolve to “Brewers”.
If the game is postponed, this market will remain open until the game has been completed.
If the game is canceled entirely, with no make-up game, this market will resolve 50-50.
To know when a postponed game will be played, please check the home team's schedule on MLB.com for the listed team and look for the game described as a makeup game.

decision.rationale: The Angels vs Brewers market price for Angels is 0.0355, implying a 3.6% chance of an Angel win. The game has already been completed and the Brewers won 9-2, confirming the Angels had essentially 0% chance at that point. The market price was already heavily weighted toward Brewers and aligns with the actual result, leaving no profitable edge.

The Brewers -1.5 spread market priced the Brewers covering at 0.85 (≈85% implied probability). The Brewers won by 7 runs, easily covering the spread. The price correctly reflected the high likelihood of a Brewers cover, so there is no mispricing to exploit.

The Over/Under 7.5 runs market priced the Over at 0.82 (≈82% implied probability). The combined total was 11 runs, so the Over hit. Given the game’s high scoring, the market’s price was appropriate and not mispriced.

market_investment_decisions.market_question: Los Angeles Angels vs. Milwaukee Brewers: O/U 7.5

decision.rationale: The NRFI (no runs in the 1st inning) market priced Yes at 0.9955 (≈99.55% implied probability). The first inning was indeed scoreless, but historically a scoreless first inning occurs far less often (~60‑70%). The market was dramatically over‑priced for the Yes side; a rational bettor would have taken the No side. Since the outcome is already known and the market is effectively settled, there is no viable bet now.

event_investment_decisions.event_description:
The FED interest rates are defined in this market by the upper bound of the target federal funds range. The decisions on the target federal fund range are made by the Federal Open Market Committee (FOMC) meetings.

This market will resolve to the amount of basis points the upper bound of the target federal funds rate is changed by versus the level it was prior to the Federal Reserve's October 2025 meeting.

If the target federal funds rate is changed to a level not expressed in the displayed options, the change will be rounded up to the nearest 25 and will resolve to the relevant bracket. (e.g. if there's a cut/increase of 12.5 bps it will be considered to be 25 bps)

The resolution source for this market is the FOMC’s statement after its meeting scheduled for October 28 - 29, 2025 according to the official calendar: https://www.federalreserve.gov/monetarypolicy/fomccalendars.htm.

The level and change of the target federal funds rate is also published at the official website of the Federal Reserve at https://www.federalreserve.gov/monetarypolicy/openmarket.htm.

This market may resolve as soon as the FOMC’s statement for their October meeting with relevant data is issued. If no statement is released by the end date of the next scheduled meeting, this market will resolve to the "No change" bracket.

decision.rationale: Recent data shows the Fed cut rates by 25 basis points on Sep 17 and futures now price an 86 % chance of another cut at the October meeting. The most likely magnitude is a further 25‑bp cut (larger cuts are not being discussed). The market’s current price for a 25‑bp cut is 0.785, implying a 78.5 % implied probability, which under‑prices the true odds I estimate at roughly 85 %. This mispricing gives a clear edge for betting on the “Yes” outcome. Confidence is high because the Reuters article cites concrete futures data and the Fed’s own statements signalling continued easing.

market_investment_decisions.market_question: Fed decreases interest rates by 25 bps after October 2025 meeting?

decision.rationale: A 50 bps or larger cut is far less likely. The Reuters piece mentions a 6 % chance of a 50‑bp cut (Investopedia also cited a similar figure). The market price is 0.0735, implying a 7.35 % probability – slightly higher than my estimate. Therefore the “Yes” side is modestly overpriced, and I take a small short position (i.e., bet against the Yes outcome) to capture the slight over‑pricing. Confidence is moderate because the underlying probability is low and any extreme move would be a surprise.

market_investment_decisions.market_question: Fed decreases interest rates by 50+ bps after October 2025 meeting?
